Ultimately, whether any regime approves or not, the human family mostly
manages to govern itself. Whether aided in the effort by "legitimate"
government or aggressively thwarted in it, what people do, is whatever it
takes to protect their own personal interests while doing what is necessary
to coexist with their neighbors. I don't even take the whole notion of
government very seriously either, frankly, but I do recognize why the
fiction of them seems to bring some comfort. Mostly it is a question of a
yin and yang conflict, between order and chaos, faith and secularism,
personal and collective, regional and national, et cetera. Neither force
can prevail more than temporarily, nor should it, and they will always
remain in conflict, as they should.

That's just how humanity operates. Anyone who tries to squeeze a parcel of
humanity into too tight a box or exercise too much force in trying to, finds the
box has all sorts of leaks and secret egresses, and that folks will unleash all
sorts of unintended consequences on anyone and their theories, when too much
power gets wielded on them. Those basic realities mean a lot more to me in
reading the human condition, than who gets to erect what border under what name
and under the pretense of what political theory.
 -- Ron Collins, on Medium 


