I should like to say two things, one intellectual and one moral. The
intellectual thing I should want to say is this: When you are studying any
matter, or considering any philosophy, ask yourself only what are the facts
and what is the truth that the facts bear out. Never let yourself be
diverted either by what you wish to believe, or by what you think would
have beneficent social effects if it were believed. But look only, and
solely, at what are the facts. That is the intellectual thing that I should
wish to say. The moral thing I should wish to say... I should say love is
wise, hatred is foolish. In this world which is getting more closely and
closely interconnected we have to learn to tolerate each other, we have to
learn to put up with the fact that some people say things that we don't
like. We can only live together in that way and if we are to live together
and not die together we must learn a kind of charity and a kind of
tolerance which is absolutely vital to the continuation of human life on
this planet.
 -- BBC's Face to Face interview of Bertrand Russell 


