of the race where that immortal garland is to be run for, not without dust
and heat. Assuredly we bring not innocence into the world, we bring
impurity much rather: that which purifies us is trial, and trial is by what
is contrary. That virtue therefore which is but a youngling in the
contemplation of evil, and knows not the utmost that vice promises to her
followers, and rejects it, is but a blank virtue, not a pure; her whiteness
