The willingness to believe garbage seems to come from a fundamental
weakness in humans: we prefer a bad explanation to no explanation, a
conspiracy theory to no theory; we can exploit patterns, even wicked
patterns, but we can't handle randomness. It would be better if we could
ensure a good harvest by sacrificing a goat. The people who believe in the
Illuminati orchestrating every disaster throughout history are actually
comforted by the belief, because a secret organization of diabolical people
in charge of everything is preferable to no one being in charge.

It also absolves the self: if something else caused this bad thing to happen it
wasn't my fault. I can stop worrying about all the things I might have done
wrong if I can attribute every problem to this bogus explanation. People who
feel guilty, maybe for legitimate reasons, are inclined to find these other junk
explanations. In parenting this is an old story: a child has a swastika on their
wall and is building a bomb in their garage over the course of months, crossing
off their classmates' names on a list with red ink, but their oblivious parents
blame the behavior on heavy metal music or violent video games after the
massacre.
 -- Mark Ferguson, on Quora 


