Justifying your feelings:

* Automatically puts you on the defense. When you're on the defense, you
  burn more energy. Rationalization can be incredibly inefficient.
* Over-complicates things.
* Perpetuates cleverness. Clever is not a good word in my personal
  dictionary. It rhymes with slick, manipulative, covert. When you're
  trying to rationalize something that is very often amorphous and insular
  you'll reach for smooth answers that you think people - or your
  subconscious - want to hear. And that makes you a salesman.
* Depresses your essential self. The more you load rationale onto your
  feelings, the more padding you create between you and your most powerful,
  unlimited resource. If you make a habit of keeping your instincts at bay,
  that tend to stay at bay.
* Makes you look and feel like a victim. In an effort to prove and protect,
  you make up reasons that appear to be more important than your refutable
  instinct. You whine. You nitpick the situation. You start sounding like
  the wimp you don't want to be - instead of the hero that you essentially
  are. When the passion is there, so is the solution. No problem looks
  insurmountable when you're turned on.
 -- Danielle LaPorte, whitehottruth.com


