is not capricious or arbitrary. No such faith comforts the software
engineer. Much of the complexity that he must master is arbitrary
complexity, forced without rhyme or reason by the many human institutions
and systems to which his interfaces must conform. These differ from
interface to interface, and from time to time, not because of necessity but
only because they were designed by different people, rather than by God.
 -- Fred Brooks, "No Silver Bullet - Essence and Accidents of Software Engineering"


