In my definition of a good relationship, people are vulnerable, and
expose themselves to the chance that they, or other people could screw
things up for them horribly, but hope the 2 or more of them are up to
dealing with the challenge when and/or if things get screwy. Realizing
that it's OK to be afraid can be liberating. It's how you react to those
fears that makes the relationship move in one direction or the other.

Personally, I tend to react *badly* to fear by either going totally self
sacrificing or withdrawing from the person I'm afraid might hurt me.
When I react *positively* to my fears, I unlock the box I keep them in,
show them around, and ask the people I'm involved with to help me out
with them.
 -- Josh Jasper, in a.p.


