Learn to distinguish the difference between errors of knowledge and
breaches of morality. An error of knowledge is not a moral flaw, provided
you are willing to correct it; only a mystic would judge human beings by
the standard of an impossible, automatic omniscience. But a breach of
morality is the conscious choice of an action you know to be evil, or a
willful evasion of knowledge, a suspension of sight and of thought. That
which you do not know, is not a moral charge against you; but that which
you refuse to know, is an account of infamy growing in your soul. Make
every allowance for errors of knowledge; do not forgive or accept any
breach of morality.
 -- Ayn Rand, "Atlas Shrugged"


