I don't think that "balance" is necessarily a good analogy for a
relationship. It is not necessary for both people in a relationship to have
transactionally equivalent benefits - for one thing, it's impossible to
define such a thing. What is necessary is that both people find the
relationship more beneficial than detrimental.
 -- Xiphias Gladius in a.p.


- If you have greater clarity about what you want, you're more likely to
  know when you're not getting it. Now what? That clarity just cost you
  some contentment.

- It's not always comfortable to realize what someone else wants. Maybe you
  learn something uncomfortable about them.

- If you ask for what you want, someone may be shocked and amazed. And if
  you're clear, you'll be aware of their shock and amazement. That may cost
  you, if you care about that person's good opinion. The shock and amazement
  may cost you your good opinion of them. Either of you may change your
  behavior toward the other.

- Getting clear about a situation may require certain actions out of you
  based on your personal ethics. That's a choice. I've run into this one
  several times in being a manager. My ethics require that I offer an
  employee a square deal, and live up to the contract we've made. When the
  company - my boss - wants to unilaterally change the deal, I've got some
  issues with that. There are things I won't do, and that costs me from
  time to time. Costs me less than the alternative, but still it isn't
  free.

Personally, I think the choice: clarity or not, is a no-brainer. That
clarity may cost you an illusion or two, however, and sometimes illusions
are comfortable and safe.
 -- James B., the SHAPE forum


I curse the lesson and bless the knowledge.
 -- Harlan Ellison


