His theory was that systems often break due to malfunction or mismatch at
the interfaces between parts. The data collection in in meters per second
but the limit setting is in feet per second. Crossed wires in a cable.
Something not plugged in. Hose not properly crimped, prone to spewing under
pressure. So after we believed a setup was totally ready to go, we'd go
back over it once more, subsystem by subsystem, listing the interfaces and
checking everything we could. We caught a lot of problems that way before
they resulted in missing data or out-of-control tests. Since then I've
always tried to remember Don Locker's Maxim. Check all interfaces. 
 -- Dan Wilder, TAG


