...there are three ways that marriages are effected biblically. We Jews,
just to be on the safe side, use all three.

The three ways are contract, purchase, and, basically, "sex with
intent."

"Contract" is pretty self-explanatory. It's a legal document between two
people which states that they're now married. "Purchase" is the reason for
wedding rings - in this method, the husband purchases the right to be
married from the wife. (The fact that the right to be married belongs to
the woman is part of why men can have multiple wives, but women can only
have one husband: women can only sell that right once, but men can buy as
many as will be sold to them.) And "sex with intent" - or, more properly,
seclusion with intent (it doesn't require actual sex, only the chance to
have sex, with intent) is the most primitive method - the two people spend
the night together, and in the morning, they're married.
 -- Xiphias Gladius, explaining Jewish laws of marriage


