"What was the difference? Why could Steve, for example, stop giving 
the free Tai Chi classes and turn to writing books with Larry Niven;
easily, no regrets, no hangups, no...

Wait a minute. What _implied_ process was I describing here? Not
the overt "Decided to, went ahead and did it" stuff; what were the
assumptions that led me to believe that Steve _should_ have had
difficulties or regrets?

As I stood there, and ran down the list, I felt a little door open
in my brain; a little reservoir of information that had been there
all along, but would not empty. 

"Permissions." That was the answer. Steve and Casey gave themselves
their _own_ permissions; they did not look to doctors, teachers, 
policemen, society, government, God, or Devil for authority. No one 
else's permission was needed - or wanted."
 -- Me, in an e-mail to Joylene


"There was no rational reason - NONE - for obeying anything other than
the dictates of my own mind. As long as I dealt with other people,
antisocial behavior of any sort would be punished according to its
degree. If I killed somebody, unless I got away with it, I would 
die. If I cheated someone, I would be putting out a signal that I
was willing to be dealt with in that manner... and would be. If
I lied, I would be forfeiting my reality to someone else's wants.
No matter what, I would be paid back in the coin in which I paid
out."
 -- Me, in an e-mail to Joylene


